<br>
Dangerous CR? I see it as a new challenge, and if its really in a dangerous spot, I hotkey a gate potion.<br>
<br>
I'm not going to go running halfway across the world to do a CR, but if there is a body in the dungeon I am in that needs a CR, I'll do it. I'm a rogue, a master of stealth, master of going undetected, and its my JOB to Retrieve Corpses in sticky situations. <br>
<br>
Along those same lines, you know what, I very very RARELY get asked for a donation for a port or a rez. I was demanded to pay for a port from a druid recently, laughed at him, waited for the next druid to arrive and they gladly ported me.<br>
<br>
Soandso class sucks or is not needed? can never get a group? Shout for hour trying to get a group? You think it's because you are a rogue? You're wrong...<br>
<br>
REPUTATION &gt; any class, level, equipment, ability, etc.<br>
<br>
Do unto others as you would have done to you? Isn't that how the quote goes? I get as much enjoyment out of CR'ing a failed EL attempt, as I do at acquiring a new item, or winning a tough fight. To be able to help people, and get their thanks, to do things that no one else can (CR from EL for example) - without costly coffins - makes me enjoy the game even more.<br>
<br>
Morathu, Clavo, Lannella - you are digging your own graves. People remember when you charged them for a CR, and they tell their friends about it. And word spreads.<br>
<br>
People also remember when you CR for free, when you see a equipped body, check to see if they are online, and offer to drag them to the zone. They remember if you tell the group at the zone in Sebelis that you will follow them down there to open the door for them, so they can do the crypt.<br>
<br>
Reputation &gt; than ANY Platinum ammount.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/ulannellalegerdemain.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lannella Legerdemain</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Druzzil Ro Member</span><br>  Posts: 58<br> <font color=#CCCCC8>(6/4/01 4:10:12 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://webhome.idirect.com/~hollow/frontshot.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fair donation for a corpse drag or lock pick?</span><hr size=1> Whoa, Woodash - I never said I did charge.  I was provoking discussion parallel to the existing discussion on charging for ports.  I just saw it interesting that we (general) discuss prices going to casters for spells (other than component costs) but I'd, personally, never seen a discussion on how to deal with the more mundane, less arcane tasks that people perform for us.<br>
<br>
I would add that, given that the *majority* of porters(etc) *do* charge for their time, I would not be adverse to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> considering</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> accepting a donation.  I don't usually take the spell/rune drops and I have to roll on or buy my own class armour.  I know that there are a lot of socially-conscious, mature individuals that frequent these boards.  No question about that.  However, folks like me have to pay those that aren't so conscious (in cash, not breeze/clarity/heals/buffs) for what we get.  I'm by no means greedy.<br>
<br>
Incidentally, my reputation is crystal.  I'm opinionated sometimes, sure, but when we're toe to toe (or toe to back) with the opponent I don't falter.  If I've ever used pickpockets in a group, I've asked first for training permission, and /split all proceeds.  I've died doing CRs for others and had to pay for my own rez/revive after.  I try not to play too many favourites, and try not to harbour any grudges.<br>
<br>
While I don't see it as my &quot;job&quot; to drag up some stranger's corpse, I'll do it if they ask me.  If I'm on my way up from the dungeon and see a corpse, I *always* check if that player is online to offer a drag.<br>
<br>
Thing is, when it comes to pickup groups, people don't know these things.  They've had a few groups with twinks bragging about something-or-other or who did pick the mob clean, and it leaves a bad taste in their mouth.  Everybody's had different experiences, some good and some bad, and some remember them more.  <br>
<br>
All I can try to do is show them how a professional rogue can operate.<br>
