</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/usomberlainwayfaerer.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Somberlain Wayfaerer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Druzzil Ro Member</span><br>  Posts: 52<br> <font color=#CCCCC8>(6/5/01 10:46:12 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fair donation for a corpse drag or lock pick?</span><hr size=1> My main character is a druid, and as such, I've made a decent amount of plat over the levels by porting.  Aside from when I could first port and &quot;advertised&quot; that I was porting to various rings for 10-20pp, I don't specify an amount.  I usually expect that people will have the decency to fork over a fair amount of cash in line with the risk or out-of-the-way nature of the destination.  If someone asks for a CS port, and then asks if 10pp is enough, my canned response is &quot;only if you provide rez or corpse retrieval if I die in the process&quot;...which generally translates to &quot;no&quot; for most of the people who ask.<br>
<br>
I've paid for many rezzes over the levels, and if I can't get my corpse, I'd happily pay for a necro or rogue to get it for me.  I play a low-level (20) rogue, and in those few levels, I've been asked to pull corpses out of fun places like Befallen, various bandit/dervish/orc camps, the Sarnak fortress in Ill Omen, and so on.  I didn't expect a donation, which is good since none is ever offered.  At low levels, I don't EXPECT people to pay for things like that, really.  But if someone is going to pay for a rez/summon/port, it seems to me that a rogue should get just as much consideration when they perform their services.  <br>
<br>
 <p>Somberlain Wayfaerer<BR>
