</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/usyrana.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Syrana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#CCCCC8>(6/10/01 4:03:23 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fair donation for a corpse drag or lock pick?</span><hr size=1> If I ask you to do something for me, I'm going to do my best to compensate you for the time and invconvience.  For example, I died recently in Sol A.  Was stupid and let too many gobs get on me.  hehe.  <br>
<br>
Well, my corpse got a bit bugged.  Others could see it at the zone line but I couldn't.  So, I petitioned, but no GM's on and no response after an hour.  So, I started looking around for Necromancers to summon it.  I sent a couple tells, which I know some consider rude and I try to avoid at all costs but I do my utmost to be extremely polite in the tell.  My second tell found me a necromancer that had some time.  I ported him to Lava, went  with him to get a coffin and escorted him to Sol A.  He summoned my corpse, which kind of worked.  <br>
<br>
It was there, I could do a /corpse and move it around, but we couldn't see it.  But, he had a great idea of doing a locate corpse which let him target it, I then /assisted him which let me target it, then I did a /loot and got my stuff.<br>
<br>
For his troubles and the cost of the coffin, I gave him 500pp.  Was it worth it to me, very much so.  He went out of his way to help me.<br>
<br>
If I'm ever in a situation where a rogue can help me get my corpse while I can't, you can bet I'll donate.  It'll probably be on the order of 100+pp as at a minimum as I would be paying 200+ for a necromancer to summon it if they weren't there.<br>
<br>
As a druid, I receive donations for ports.  Haven't accepted money for SOW's and other buffs since I was like 18 and didn't have enough money to buy my spells.  So, I am all too happy to give back some of that money to others.<br>
